Here's the full migration. Three critical breaking changes drive this rewrite:

## Breaking Changes in .NET 8

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Cannot force-kill threads |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Dead code |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<WorkItem> _channel;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public BackgroundProcessor()
    {
        _channel = Channel.CreateBounded<WorkItem>(new BoundedChannelOptions(100)
        {
            FullMode = BoundedChannelFullMode.Wait
        });
    }

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            try
            {
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, ct);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handling
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit gracefully — no ResetAbort equivalent needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        // Signal no more items will be written
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();

        // Wait for graceful drain, then cancel if still running
        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            using var gracePeriod = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout.Value);
            try
            {
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(gracePeriod.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Graceful drain timed out — cancel in-flight work
                await _cts.CancelAsync();
                await _workerTask; // wait for cancellation to propagate
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

**1. `CancellationToken` is cooperative — not preemptive.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works if your code checks the token. Long-running CPU work must call `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` periodically:

```csharp
private async Task ProcessItemAsync(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    foreach (var chunk in item.Chunks)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // ← must do this manually
        await HandleChunkAsync(chunk);
    }
}
```

**2. Blocking calls (`GetNextItem()`) won't respond to cancellation.**
The old code's `GetNextItem()` that blocks a thread is replaced by `Channel<T>.ReadAllAsync(ct)`, which is natively cancellable. If you're wrapping a legacy blocking API, use:

```csharp
// Wraps a synchronous blocking call so it respects cancellation
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(), ct);
```

⚠️ This doesn't actually interrupt the blocking call — it just abandons the `Task`. If `GetNextItem()` blocks forever, the thread leaks. Refactor the blocking API if possible.

**3. `volatile bool _running` is insufficient for async.**
The old `volatile bool` flag can't unblock a thread stuck in `GetNextItem()`. `CancellationToken` propagates into async APIs and throws at suspension points automatically.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` has no equivalent — and doesn't need one.**
`OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception. Catch it, clean up, and exit. There's no auto-rethrow behavior to suppress.

**5. Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.**
`CTS` allocates a timer internally when used with timeouts. Implement `IAsyncDisposable` (as shown) to avoid leaks.
